  {
    "_creationTime": 1774911531963.552,
    "_id": "jn786nwb8hy35xm4fbj2cmepbh83wj84",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "Distributed agent work queue pattern: each machine runs a polling loop (analogous to drain-beads.sh) against Provenance. When ready work is found, the agent claims it atomically, noscope mints a scoped Provenance API key via a provider script, the agent executes the task with only the permissions its scope grants, posts results back to Provenance, and noscope revokes the credential. Machines self-organize based on available compute. Requires: (1) Provenance API endpoint for creating scoped, short-lived API keys with specific permission sets (e.g., read-only on project X), (2) Provenance API endpoint for revoking keys by ID before TTL expiry, (3) a noscope provider script wrapping these endpoints, (4) a task readiness/claim protocol in Provenance (similar to bd ready / bd update --claim). This enables cross-team agent coordination without central dispatch -- an agent on Ben's machine can pick up work from Bob's project by minting credentials scoped to Bob's Provenance graph.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [
      {
        "clause": "Distributed agent work queue pattern derived from drain-beads.sh, noscope provider contract, and Provenance knowledge graph",
        "sourceId": "k17ee2jba6yj27d0jg2cmnbcd583wa0e"
      },
      {
        "clause": "Proposes Convex-native pub/sub work queue: ephemeral workItems table with OCC claiming, credential-as-heartbeat via noscope, Provenance graph mutations as event publishers, thread messages as durable audit trail",
        "sourceId": "k172g8p9wxc2e5ysq4er08ddnh83zbhr"
      }
    ],
    "statement": "Provenance shall support short-lived, scoped API key minting and revocation compatible with noscope's provider contract, enabling agents on networked machines to poll for ready tasks, claim work atomically, execute with scoped credentials, and post results back without a central dispatcher",
    "stats": {
      "childCount": 2.0,
      "openQuestionCount": 0.0,
      "resolutionCount": 0.0,
      "ruleCount": 0.0
    },
    "status": "discovery",
    "updatedAt": 1774924039060.0
  },
  {
    "_creationTime": 1774925404113.0176,
    "_id": "jn7ayf9t9fs2np6wbd1hyxe2wx83z3p4",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "When the Provenance knowledge graph changes — a source is added, a requirement is created, a comment is posted, a resolution is proposed — the right expertise needs to engage with that change. Today this is manual: a human runs drain-beads.sh, or asks an agent in an ad-hoc session. This has proven valuable but doesn't scale and depends on a human remembering to trigger it.\n\nThe system should: (1) observe Provenance graph mutations as events, (2) match each event against configurable engagement rules that specify which roles should respond, (3) create scoped work for agents with matching roles to pick up, (4) agents execute with role-scoped credentials (via noscope) limited to exactly the permissions their role grants, (5) results flow back as durable Provenance thread messages.\n\nRoles serve dual purpose — they define both the credential scope (what the agent CAN do) and the engagement type (what the agent SHOULD do). The four Provenance roles (read-only, contributor, analyst, admin) map to engagement patterns: an analyst reviews sources and assesses rule impact; a contributor discusses requirements and proposes resolutions; an admin approves resolutions and activates rules. Engagement rules are configurable per project, e.g.: 'source.create -> assign:analyst', 'requirement.status:refinement -> assign:contributor', 'rule.status:review -> assign:analyst,admin'.\n\nThis is NOT a general-purpose workflow engine. It is a focused system for getting the right eyes (human or agent) on Provenance graph changes at the right time with the right permissions.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [
      {
        "clause": "Research on event-driven agent engagement patterns, role-scoped credential lifecycle, and configurable engagement rules",
        "sourceId": "k172g8p9wxc2e5ysq4er08ddnh83zbhr"
      },
      {
        "clause": "Original design conversation establishing the distributed agent work queue pattern and self-organizing machine concept",
        "sourceId": "k17ee2jba6yj27d0jg2cmnbcd583wa0e"
      },
      {
        "clause": "Session trails and --reason flag provide the durable audit trail, freeing work items to be ephemeral coordination primitives",
        "sourceId": "k170kqm3q6c71je2tvqb62akrn83zgx6"
      },
      {
        "clause": "UI concept prototypes informing resolution on dedicated resolution page, review queue, withering vocabulary, and field notes evolution",
        "sourceId": "k17atjfmksc11fkagxe2wgb3ss83y41k"
      }
    ],
    "statement": "Provenance shall automatically engage agents with appropriate role-scoped credentials when graph changes occur, enabling configurable, event-driven ideation and review across sources, requirements, resolutions, and rules without manual dispatch",
    "stats": {
      "childCount": 23.0,
      "openQuestionCount": 0.0,
      "resolutionCount": 11.0,
      "ruleCount": 1.0
    },
    "status": "discovery",
    "updatedAt": 1774945294980.0
  },
  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946004773.5264,
    "_id": "jn712t9gh9292f7t962g16878n83ys60",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The first-time experience IS the product thesis compressed into sixty seconds. A product person arrives. They have a problem. They describe it the way they would describe it to a colleague: 'Checkout is confusing and we're losing people at the payment step.' That sentence hits an empty canvas and becomes the first territory on their product map.\n\nWhat happens next is the aha moment: within minutes — before the user comes back, ideally before they close the tab — an agent has begun exploring that territory. It pulls whatever context exists (sources already in the project, the statement itself, linked references if any), posts field notes as thread messages, and starts building the initial topology. 'I found three areas to investigate: payment form complexity, session timeout during checkout, and mobile-specific layout issues. Here's what I see in each...'\n\nThe first-time experience must communicate three things without saying them:\n1. You describe problems. We map them. (Not: you write specs. Not: you create tickets.)\n2. The map builds itself. (Not: you assign work. Not: you manage sprints.)\n3. Come back and the territory has been explored. (Not: nothing happened because nobody was assigned.)\n\nWhat the user does NOT see: requirement, status, discovery, engagement, work item, credential. What the user DOES see: their problem, in their words, on a map that is already being explored.\n\nThe empty state is not an empty dashboard with a 'Create your first project' button. The empty state is an invitation: 'What problem are you solving?' One text field. No other chrome. The product begins when they answer.\n\nAnti-patterns to reject:\n- Onboarding tours (the product should be obvious)\n- Template galleries ('Choose a template for your product map')\n- Feature discovery tooltips\n- Empty dashboards with illustrations of what could be here\n- Any language that presupposes the user understands the data model\n\nThe input surface accepts natural language. Period. The system parses intent, not structure. If someone types 'our API is slow and customers are complaining,' that becomes a discovery requirement. If someone types 'we need to support SAML SSO by Q3,' that becomes a discovery requirement. The maturity of the input varies; the entry point does not.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "When a user opens Provenance for the first time with an empty project, the product shall present a single input surface that accepts a problem described in natural language — not a form, not a template, not a wizard — and immediately create a discovery-status requirement, triggering agent exploration that produces visible results before the user's next visit",
    "stats": {
      "childCount": 0.0,
      "openQuestionCount": 0.0,
      "resolutionCount": 0.0,
      "ruleCount": 0.0
    },
    "status": "discovery",
    "updatedAt": 1774946004773.0
  },
  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946028595.49,
    "_id": "jn70dw8g6f95gqzv8s253f2zfh83z8hm",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The daily experience defines the product more than any other moment. This is where Provenance either feels like a living atlas or collapses into another dashboard.\n\nWhat the returning user sees first: their product map. Not a list of recent activity. Not a notification feed. Not a kanban board. A spatial representation of the product they are building — the territories they have mapped (requirements with rules and sources), the territories under exploration (requirements in discovery with active agent engagement), the territories that need their decision (requirements with pending resolutions), and the blank spots where the map ends and unknown territory begins.\n\nThe primary action surface is the review queue — 'Proposed Atlas Edits.' These are draft resolutions where agents have explored territory and are proposing how to extend or refine the map. Each proposed edit is a composed document: what the agent found (field notes/thread messages), what they propose (resolution position and rationale), how confident they are, and what would change on the map if approved. The user reads, thinks, approves or pushes back.\n\nThis is fundamentally different from every competitor:\n- Jira/Linear: you open it and see tasks assigned to people with due dates\n- Notion: you open it and see pages someone wrote\n- Confluence: you open it and see documentation nobody maintains\n- Provenance: you open it and see your product, mapped, with proposed extensions\n\nThe map communicates completeness spatially. A well-mapped territory has thick connections — sources, rules, resolutions linking to requirements that link to each other. A poorly-mapped territory has thin connections — a lone requirement with no sources, no rules, no resolutions. The user doesn't need a 'coverage report' — they can SEE the thin spots.\n\nActive engagement is visible but not noisy. When an agent is currently exploring a territory, the node has presence — a subtle animation, a warm glow, field notes appearing in real-time if the user is watching. But it never interrupts. The user is not a manager supervising workers. They are a cartographer reviewing proposed additions to their atlas.\n\nThe return visit must never feel like email triage. There is no inbox. There are proposed map edits, which you evaluate on their merits. There is territory you can explore by navigating the map. There is the option to drop a new problem anywhere on the map ('What about accessibility? We haven't thought about that.') and watch it become new territory for exploration.\n\nThe navigation metaphor is spatial: zoom in to see detail (rules, specific thread discussions), zoom out to see topology (which territories connect, where the dead ends are, what has foundations and what doesn't). The existing semantic zoom in the Provenance UI already does this — it just needs to become the primary experience rather than a visualization feature.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "When a product person with an active project opens Provenance, the product shall present their product as a navigable map showing explored territory, unmapped regions, and areas requiring their decision — with 'proposed atlas edits' (draft resolutions) as the primary call to action, not a feed, not a dashboard, not a task list",
