  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946054295.4768,
    "_id": "jn79e02xw20t6t5te5b0w1nh3983yckt",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The new-joiner experience is the acid test for whether Provenance is truly a self-propelling atlas or just another tool with accumulated state.\n\nSix months into a project, the product map has hundreds of nodes. Requirements at various maturity stages. Dozens of resolutions — some approved, some superseded, some rejected. Rules linked to requirements linked to sources. Thread discussions capturing months of agent and human analysis.\n\nA new person joins the team. They open Provenance. What happens?\n\nIn Jira: they see a backlog of 400 tickets and have no idea which ones matter or why they exist. They ask colleagues. They read a stale wiki page titled 'Project Overview (Last Updated 8 Months Ago).' They spend two weeks building mental context through osmosis.\n\nIn Provenance: they see a product map. They can start anywhere — pick a territory that looks interesting or relevant to their role. They click on a rule: 'Payment processing shall timeout after 30 seconds.' They see WHY: it traces to a resolution ('We chose 30 seconds based on p99 latency analysis of payment gateways') which traces to a requirement ('Checkout reliability — users are abandoning at payment') which traces to a source ('Customer support tickets Q1 2026: 47% mention payment failures'). The full chain. The reasoning. The evidence.\n\nThey can read the thread discussion that led to the resolution — the field notes from the agent that explored this territory, the critique from the analyst that stress-tested the approach, the human's decision to approve. They don't need to ask anyone why the timeout is 30 seconds. The map contains its own explanation.\n\nThis is the self-propelling property at work: because documentation IS the collaboration (not a second job after the collaboration), it is always current. The new joiner reads the same artifacts that the team produced while doing their actual work. Nothing was written 'for the wiki.' Everything was written as part of the product mapping process.\n\nKey navigational patterns for new joiners:\n1. Top-down: start from high-level requirements, zoom into the territories beneath them\n2. Bottom-up: start from a specific rule or behavior, trace upward to understand why it exists\n3. Lateral: follow edges between requirements to understand how territories connect\n4. Temporal: read thread discussions chronologically to understand how thinking evolved (the one case where time matters — not for project management, but for understanding the intellectual journey)\n\nWhat Provenance must NOT do for new joiners:\n- Generate a summary document (that's a wiki pretending to be a map)\n- Provide a 'Getting Started' guide (the product IS the guide)\n- Require someone to explain the project (the map explains itself)\n- Show a chronological history of changes (that's a changelog, not an atlas)\n\nThe test: can a new team member, in their first hour, trace any product behavior back to the problem it solves and the evidence that the problem exists? If yes, the atlas is working. If no, we have a wiki in disguise.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "When a new team member joins a project with an existing product map, Provenance shall enable them to understand why any artifact exists by navigating traceability edges — from any rule to the decision that created it, to the problem it addresses, to the evidence that the problem exists — without requiring tribal knowledge, onboarding documents, or asking colleagues",
