  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946080999.389,
    "_id": "jn7e8gdfkb2zyyc0hb1afqdy3d83yhm7",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The hardest product problem is not building the features. It is communicating what the product IS when it doesn't fit an existing category.\n\nProvenance is not project management (no sprints, no velocity, no assignments, no due dates). It is not a wiki (you don't write pages, pages precipitate from collaboration). It is not a task tracker (no kanban, no status columns, no burndown). It is not documentation (documentation is a byproduct, not the purpose). It is not an AI chatbot (agents work autonomously, they don't wait for prompts).\n\nThe product must communicate this through WHAT IT DOES, not through WHAT IT SAYS ABOUT ITSELF.\n\nWhen someone expects Jira and opens Provenance, their confusion must resolve through interaction, not through reading an explainer. They look for 'Create Task' and find 'What problem are you solving?' They look for 'Assign to' and find no one to assign to — the map explores itself. They look for 'Sprint Planning' and find a product atlas with territories at different levels of exploration. They look for 'Due Date' and find that completeness is spatial, not temporal.\n\nEach missing feature is a statement: we didn't forget sprints. We rejected them. The product is making an argument through its structure.\n\nWhat the product experience must communicate:\n1. Problems are the entry point, not tasks. (The input surface accepts problems in natural language.)\n2. The product maps itself. (Agents explore without being assigned.)\n3. Decisions are first-class objects, not comments on tickets. (Resolutions have their own pages with context, position, rationale.)\n4. Everything traces back to evidence. (Every rule connects to a decision connects to a problem connects to a source.)\n5. Documentation is the work, not a record of the work. (There is no 'write docs' step because the atlas IS the documentation.)\n\nWhat the product experience must NOT do:\n- Include a comparison page ('How Provenance differs from Jira')\n- Include onboarding text explaining the data model\n- Include tooltips defining terms (if the terms need defining, the terms are wrong)\n- Include a dashboard that could be mistaken for a project management tool\n- Include any temporal visualization as a primary view (timelines, Gantt charts, burndowns)\n\nThe vocabulary IS the product:\n- 'Problem' not 'ticket' or 'issue' or 'story'\n- 'Evidence' not 'attachment' or 'reference'\n- 'Decision' not 'comment' or 'status change'\n- 'Territory' or 'area' not 'epic' or 'project'\n- 'Explore' not 'assign' or 'work on'\n- 'Proposed map edit' not 'pull request' or 'change request'\n\nThe vocabulary should feel natural and self-evident, not jargon-laden or metaphor-heavy. A product person should never think 'what does this tool call things?' They should think 'oh, this makes sense.' If the cartographic metaphor leaks into user-facing labels (Unmapped Region, Territory, Atlas), evaluate whether it clarifies or confuses. The metaphor is powerful for internal understanding — it may or may not be the right surface language.\n\nThe test: if someone uses Provenance for a week, do they explain it to a colleague using our vocabulary or using Jira's vocabulary? If they say 'it's like a map of our product where agents explore the problems we drop in and propose how to extend it,' the identity landed. If they say 'it's like Jira but with AI,' we failed.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "Provenance shall communicate its identity through the product experience itself — the absence of sprints, velocity charts, assignees, due dates, and kanban boards IS the statement; the presence of problems, evidence, decisions, and traceability IS the explanation — without relying on marketing copy, onboarding text, or 'what is Provenance?' pages to explain the category",
