  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946102097.8936,
    "_id": "jn78gr4wwdg4atf54b15y4wk1x83zh64",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "Every great product has a moment where the user's mental model shifts. For Dropbox it was 'I saved a file on my laptop and it was on my phone.' For Slack it was 'I can see what my team discussed while I was asleep.' For Google it was 'I typed three words and found the exact page.'\n\nFor Provenance, the aha moment is: 'I described a problem, went to lunch, and came back to find an agent had researched it, identified three sub-problems, found supporting evidence, and proposed a structured breakdown for my review.'\n\nThis is not an AI chatbot experience (where you prompt and wait for a response). This is not a task management experience (where you assign work and check on progress). This is a living map experience — you drop a pin on unexplored territory, and when you come back, a cartographer has surveyed it and drafted a map extension for your approval.\n\nThe aha moment has three components:\n1. AUTONOMY: nobody was assigned. The product person didn't select an agent, didn't choose a role, didn't set a priority. They described a problem and the system engaged.\n2. QUALITY: the exploration is substantive. The agent didn't just reformulate the problem — it pulled in evidence, traced connections to existing territories, identified dimensions the user hadn't considered, and synthesized findings into a coherent proposal.\n3. RESPECT: the agent didn't act. It proposed. The draft resolution sits in the review queue as a 'proposed atlas edit,' awaiting the product person's judgment. The human is the cartographer-in-chief. The agent is a field researcher presenting findings.\n\nThe aha moment must happen on the FIRST return visit, not the tenth. If the user drops their first problem and comes back to silence — no field notes, no proposed resolution, no evidence of exploration — the product has failed. The engagement engine, the work items, the credential system, the mutation triggers — all of that infrastructure exists to make this one moment happen reliably.\n\nTiming matters: the aha moment should occur within minutes of dropping a problem, not hours. If the project has existing sources and context, the exploration should begin immediately and produce initial field notes within 2-5 minutes. If the project is empty (first problem ever), the agent should still produce a structural analysis of the problem statement itself — dimensions to explore, questions to investigate, related areas to consider.\n\nThe aha moment is not a feature. It is the product.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "Provenance shall deliver the 'aha moment' — the experience that makes a user realize this is a fundamentally different product — through the return visit: the user drops a problem, leaves, and returns to find that territory explored with field notes, proposed structure, and a draft resolution ready for their review, without anyone being assigned or managed",
