  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946155085.2756,
    "_id": "jn7daw85fv011wwbz53281nvjs83ygw9",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The product map is not a graph visualization. It is a cartographic representation of a product's self-knowledge. The visual language must communicate completeness spatially, the way a real atlas communicates explored versus unexplored territory.\n\nWell-mapped territory: a requirement with sources tracing to evidence, resolutions capturing decisions, rules defining behaviors, and thread discussions recording the exploration process. Visually dense. Thick connections. The territory has been surveyed, mapped, and documented. On the canvas, these nodes sit in a cluster of connected artifacts — you can SEE the substance.\n\nThinly-mapped territory: a requirement exists, maybe with a source or two, but no resolutions, no rules. The problem has been identified but not explored. Visually sparse. The node sits with thin connections extending into nothing. The map is saying: 'Someone noticed this territory exists, but nobody has surveyed it.'\n\nUnmapped regions: the absence that is visible. If a requirement has three child territories and one of those children has rich connections while the other two are sparse, the map communicates an imbalance. Structural analysis (an agent capability) can identify implied territories — 'You have requirements for authentication and authorization but nothing about session management. That territory is implied but unmapped.'\n\nThe existing Provenance UI has semantic zoom — zoom 0 shows just node types and colors, zoom 1 shows summaries, zoom 2 shows full detail. The spatial completeness indicators should layer into this:\n- Zoom 0: density is visible through connection thickness and node clustering. Well-mapped areas are visually heavy. Sparse areas are visually light. Unmapped areas are... absent, but their absence is notable because of the structure around them.\n- Zoom 1: badges or indicators showing coverage metrics per territory — '3 sources, 2 resolutions, 5 rules' vs '0 sources, 0 resolutions, 0 rules'\n- Zoom 2: full detail with every connection visible, thread discussions readable, traceability paths explorable\n\nThe withering vocabulary from the UI evolution resolution also applies here:\n- Abandoned artifacts: reduced opacity, dashed borders. History remains readable but clearly past.\n- Superseded artifacts: amber hatching with link to replacement. The palimpsest — old visible under new.\n- Contradicted artifacts: cross-hatching, contested boundary markers.\n- Active/explored: solid, warm, present.\n- New/unexplored: breathing animation, line hatching — the map inviting exploration.\n\nThe product person should be able to glance at their product map and say: 'Payment is well-mapped. Checkout is partially explored. We haven't touched accessibility at all.' That assessment should take seconds, not reports.",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "Provenance shall present the product map with spatial completeness indicators — visually distinguishing well-mapped territories (dense connections, sources, rules, resolutions) from thinly-mapped territories (isolated requirements, missing evidence, no decisions) and unmapped regions (areas implied by existing structure but not yet explored) — so that product coverage is perceived, not counted",
    "stats": {
