  {
    "_creationTime": 1774946684758.133,
    "_id": "jn74k4cw6720bphep9g28anags83yyhr",
    "createdBy": "kd795pd2q713d3q8q22z5d4a7s822ec0",
    "description": "The human review experience is the core product interaction. When a human runs 'statesman provenance resolutions review <id>' in the CLI, or opens a resolution in the web UI, they see ONE composed view. Not a scavenger hunt across separate screens.\n\nThe composed view presents, top-to-bottom:\n1. Resolution title and status badge (draft/review)\n2. Parent artifact statement and status — the thing this resolution addresses\n3. Context — what the agent observed (prose, not bullet points)\n4. Position — what the agent recommends (the proposed action)\n5. Rationale — why this recommendation (the argument)\n6. Confidence score — 0.0-1.0 with visual indicator\n7. Enforcement classification — regulatory/policy/specification\n8. Informing thread messages — the field notes that led to this resolution, with agent/human role badges, ordered chronologically. These are the tributaries that flow into this confluence point.\n9. Source references — linked evidence from the parent requirement's source refs\n10. Action buttons — Approve, Reject (with reason), Request Revision\n\nThe CLI version renders this as structured terminal output. The web version renders it as a typeset document with margin column for source citations (per the UI evolution resolution). Both share the same Convex query composition.\n\nThe review queue ('statesman provenance resolutions list --status review') shows a filterable list of resolutions awaiting review: title, parent artifact, confidence, age, field note count.\n\nCreated by: Steve Jobs (agent: resolution workflow decomposition)",
    "projectId": "9887a770-ff7d-44d4-aeeb-a9c7b2252b73",
    "sourceRefs": [],
    "statement": "The resolution review experience shall compose resolution context, position, rationale, confidence, informing thread messages, and parent artifact into a single reviewable unit in both CLI and web interfaces",
